    summary: `This chapter explores the essential tools and methods psychologists use to study behavior scientifically. The scientific method — a systematic cycle of observation, hypothesis formation, experimentation, and data analysis — forms the backbone of all psychological research. Key research designs include experiments (which establish cause-and-effect by manipulating independent variables and measuring dependent variables), correlational studies (which reveal relationships but cannot prove causation), surveys, naturalistic observation, and case studies. Rigorous methodology requires control groups, random assignment, and double-blind procedures to eliminate bias. Equally important are the ethical guidelines governing research with human participants — including informed consent, the right to withdraw, debriefing after participation, and strict confidentiality — which were strengthened after controversial studies like Milgram's obedience experiments highlighted the need for stronger participant protections.`,
    summaryKa: `ეს თავი იკვლევს აუცილებელ ინსტრუმენტებსა და მეთოდებს, რომლებსაც ფსიქოლოგები იყენებენ ქცევის მეცნიერულად შესასწავლად. სამეცნიერო მეთოდი ქმნის ფსიქოლოგიური კვლევის ხერხემალს. ძირითადი კვლევის დიზაინები მოიცავს ექსპერიმენტებს, კორელაციურ კვლევებს, გამოკითხვებს, ბუნებრივ დაკვირვებას და შემთხვევის შესწავლას. მკაცრი მეთოდოლოგია მოითხოვს საკონტროლო ჯგუფებს, შემთხვევით განაწილებას და ორმაგად ბრმა პროცედურებს.`,
    summaryRu: `В этой главе рассматриваются основные инструменты и методы, которые психологи используют для научного изучения поведения. Научный метод составляет основу всех психологических исследований. Основные планы исследований включают эксперименты, корреляционные исследования, опросы, естественное наблюдение и тематические исследования. Строгая методология требует контрольных групп, случайного распределения и двойных слепых процедур.`,
    summaryHy: `Այս գլուխն ուսումնասիրում է էական գործիքներն ու մեթոդները, որոնք հոգեբաններն օգտագործում են վարքը գիտականորեն ուսումնասիրելու համար: Գիտական մեթոդը կազմում է բոլոր հոգեբանական հետազոտությունների ողնաշարը: Հիմնական հետազոտական նախագծերը ներառում են փորձարկումներ, կորելացիոն ուսումնասիրություններ, հարցումներ, բնական դիտարկում և դեպքերի ուսումնասիրություն:`,
    summaryAz: `Bu fəsil psixoloqların davranışı elmi cəhətdən öyrənmək üçün istifadə etdikləri əsas alətləri və metodları araşdırır. Elmi metod bütün psixoloji tədqiqatların onurğa sütununu təşkil edir. Əsas tədqiqat dizaynlarına təcrübələr, korrelyasiya tədqiqatları, sorğular, naturalist müşahidə və hal tədqiqatları daxildir.`,
    keyPoints: [
      `The scientific method is psychology's foundation: a systematic process of Observation (noticing a phenomenon), Hypothesis (forming a testable prediction), Experiment (testing under controlled conditions), Data Analysis (using statistics to interpret results), and Theory (building broader explanations). This cycle is repeated and refined over time.`,
      `In experiments, the independent variable is what the researcher manipulates, and the dependent variable is what is measured. The experimental group receives the treatment while the control group does not, allowing researchers to isolate cause and effect through direct comparison.`,
      `Correlation measures the relationship between two variables (ranging from -1.0 to +1.0), but correlation does NOT equal causation. A strong correlation between ice cream sales and drowning does not mean ice cream causes drowning — a third variable (hot weather) explains both.`,
      `Sampling and assignment are critical: random sampling (every person has an equal chance of being selected) ensures the sample represents the population, while random assignment (placing participants in groups by chance) controls for confounding variables in experiments.`,
      `Research methods beyond experiments: naturalistic observation (watching behavior in natural settings), surveys (questionnaires or interviews of large samples), case studies (in-depth investigation of one individual or group), and longitudinal studies (following the same participants over months or years to track change).`,
      `Double-blind procedures (neither participants nor researchers know who is in which group) eliminate both placebo effects and experimenter bias. Single-blind designs hide group assignment only from participants. These controls are essential for objective results.`,
      `Ethical guidelines protect research participants: informed consent (knowing what to expect), right to withdraw at any time, debriefing (explaining the true purpose afterward), confidentiality, and minimal risk. These principles were strengthened after controversial studies like Milgram's obedience experiments and Zimbardo's prison study.`
    ],
